.TH "PKGD" "1" "July 7, 2026" "pkg\-defender 1.0.4" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
pkgd \(em supply chain attack defense CLI
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]pkgd\f[R] [\f[I]OPTIONS\f[R]] \f[I]COMMAND\f[R]
[\f[I]ARGS\f[R]\&...]
.PP
\f[B]pkgd\f[R] [\f[I]OPTIONS\f[R]] \f[I]MANAGER\f[R]
\f[I]SUBCOMMAND\f[R] [\f[I]PACKAGE\f[R]\&...]
[\f[I]MANAGER_OPTIONS\f[R]\&...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]pkg\-defender\f[R] is a supply chain security tool that intercepts
package manager commands to check packages against known threats and
cooldown policies before they are installed.
It supports wrapping package managers such as npm, pip, brew, cargo, and
others transparently.
.PP
When invoked with a known package manager name as the first argument,
\f[B]pkgd\f[R] intercepts the command, performs security checks (threat
database lookup and cooldown verification), and either allows or blocks
the operation.
When invoked with a native subcommand, it provides threat intelligence,
auditing, configuration, and system management features.
.SH COMMANDS
.SS Common Commands
.TP
\f[B]setup\f[R]
Run the first\-time setup wizard to configure feeds, API tokens, and
initial settings.
.TP
\f[B]status\f[R]
Show defender status including intelligence feed health, active
bypasses, and threat counts by severity.
Use \f[B]\-\-feeds\f[R] for per\-feed details.
.TP
\f[B]audit\f[R] \f[I]PATH\f[R]
Scan a project\(cqs dependency lock file for known vulnerabilities and
cooldown\-pending packages.
Supports package\-lock.json, poetry.lock, requirements.txt, yarn.lock,
pnpm\-lock.yaml, Pipfile.lock, and uv.lock.
Use \f[B]\-\-deep\f[R] to also check cooldown status for each package.
Use \f[B]\-\-fail\-on\-threat\f[R] to exit with code 4 on CRITICAL/HIGH
findings.
.TP
\f[B]bypass\f[R] \f[I]PACKAGE_SPEC\f[R] \f[B]\-\-reason\f[R] \f[I]TEXT\f[R]
Create a bypass entry that allows a specific package version to skip all
safety checks.
\f[B]WARNING:\f[R] This disables cooldown and threat detection for the
specified package.
Requires \f[B]\-\-reason\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]health\f[R]
Run system diagnostics: checks config file accessibility, database
connectivity, WAL mode, feed sync status, API token validity, disk
space, and file permissions.
Use \f[B]\-\-verbose\f[R] for detailed diagnostics.
.TP
\f[B]reset\f[R]
Reset all pkg\-defender data.
Without \f[B]\-\-teardown\f[R], only the threat database is deleted.
With \f[B]\-\-teardown\f[R], the config file and daemon service are also
removed.
.SS Management Commands
.TP
\f[B]config\f[R]
Manage configuration settings.
Subcommands: \f[I]view\f[R], \f[I]list\f[R], \f[I]set\f[R],
\f[I]get\f[R], \f[I]set\-secret\f[R], \f[I]options\f[R],
\f[I]reset\f[R].
.RS
.TP
\f[B]config view\f[R] [\f[B]\-\-json\f[R]]
Display the current configuration (all sections).
Secret values are masked as \f[CR][SECRET]\f[R].
With \f[B]\-\-json\f[R] output is JSON.
.TP
\f[B]config list\f[R] [\f[B]\-\-json\f[R]]
List all current configuration values with their sources.
The source column shows whether each value comes from the default or an
environment variable.
.TP
\f[B]config set\f[R] \f[I]KEY\f[R] \f[I]VALUE\f[R]
Set a configuration value (e.g.,
\f[CR]config set output.color false\f[R]).
Values are type\-coerced to the target field\(cqs type before writing.
.TP
\f[B]config get\f[R] \f[I]KEY\f[R]
Get a specific configuration value.
Secret values are masked.
.TP
\f[B]config set\-secret\f[R] \f[I]KEY\f[R]
Set a secret value with hidden input (API tokens, etc.).
Masked on output.
.TP
\f[B]config options\f[R]
List all configurable options with their dotted path, type, default, and
description.
.TP
\f[B]config reset\f[R]
Reset configuration to defaults (preserves the config file location and
\f[CR][SECRET]\f[R] entries).
.RE
.TP
\f[B]intel\f[R]
Threat intelligence feed commands.
Subcommands: \f[I]sync\f[R], \f[I]search\f[R], \f[I]report\f[R].
.RS
.TP
\f[B]intel sync\f[R] [\f[B]\-\-output\f[R] \f[I]FORMAT\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-pretty\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-json\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-exclude\-feed\f[R] \f[I]FEED\f[R]]
Sync threat intelligence from all configured feeds.
Feeds: OSV, GHSA, Socket.dev, npm Advisory, OSSF Malicious, Mastodon,
Reddit, RSS, X/Twitter.
Homebrew is auto\-included when \f[CR]brew\f[R] is on \f[CR]$PATH\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]intel search\f[R] \f[I]QUERY\f[R] [\f[B]\-\-manager\f[R] \f[I]NAME\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-output\f[R] \f[I]FORMAT\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-pretty\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-json\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-exclude\-severity\f[R] \f[I]LIST\f[R]]
Search the local threat database for packages or vulnerabilities.
Use \f[B]\-\-manager\f[R] to filter by ecosystem.
.TP
\f[B]intel report\f[R] [\f[B]\-\-output\f[R] \f[I]FORMAT\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-pretty\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-json\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-manager\f[R] \f[I]NAME\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-exclude\-severity\f[R] \f[I]LIST\f[R]]
Display a threat intelligence report showing recent threats (last 7
days), severity breakdown, source breakdown, ecosystem analysis (last 30
days), and top targeted packages (last 30 days).
.RE
.TP
\f[B]daemon\f[R]
Background daemon management commands.
Subcommands: \f[I]run\f[R], \f[I]start\f[R], \f[I]stop\f[R],
\f[I]restart\f[R], \f[I]status\f[R], \f[I]install\f[R],
\f[I]uninstall\f[R].
.RS
.TP
\f[B]daemon run\f[R]
Run daemon in the foreground (for service managers like
systemd/launchd).
.TP
\f[B]daemon start\f[R]
Start the background sync daemon (writes PID file at
\f[CR]daemon.pid\f[R] in the data directory).
.TP
\f[B]daemon stop\f[R]
Stop the running daemon (SIGTERM with 5s grace, then SIGKILL).
.TP
\f[B]daemon restart\f[R]
Stop the running daemon (if any) and start a new background process.
.TP
\f[B]daemon status\f[R]
Show daemon status from heartbeat and PID file.
.TP
\f[B]daemon install\f[R] [\f[B]\-\-user\f[R]]
Install the daemon as a system service (launchd on macOS, systemd on
Linux, scheduled task on Windows) for automatic startup.
.TP
\f[B]daemon uninstall\f[R]
Remove the daemon system service.
.RE
.SS Other Commands
.TP
\f[B]hooks\f[R]
Generate shell functions for transparent package manager wrapping.
Detects installed shells and package managers, then prints functions
that can be added to your shell RC file.
Each function conditionally routes dangerous subcommands through pkgd
while passing safe commands directly to the real binary.
.TP
\f[B]completion generate\f[R] \f[I]SHELL\f[R]
Generate shell completion script for the specified shell.
Supports bash, zsh, fish, powershell, and nushell.
.TP
\f[B]audit\-logs query\f[R] [\f[B]\-\-ecosystem\f[R] \f[I]NAME\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-package\f[R] \f[I]NAME\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-verdict\f[R] \f[I]NAME\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-source\f[R] \f[I]NAME\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-since\f[R] \f[I]ISO\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-until\f[R] \f[I]ISO\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-limit\f[R] \f[I]N\f[R]]
Query audit event logs with optional filters for ecosystem, package,
verdict, source, and time range.
.TP
\f[B]audit\-logs stats\f[R]
Show aggregate audit statistics including counts by verdict, ecosystem,
and source.
.TP
\f[B]db snapshot\f[R] [\f[B]\-\-download\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-verify\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-latest\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-force\f[R]]
Database snapshot management.
\f[B]\-\-download\f[R] fetches a snapshot with SHA256 verification (from
GitHub Releases or custom URL).
\f[B]\-\-verify\f[R] checks the SHA256 and integrity of the local
database.
\f[B]\-\-latest\f[R] shows the latest available snapshot version on
GitHub.
\f[B]\-\-force\f[R] replaces an existing database.
.TP
\f[B]db verify\f[R]
Verify local database integrity and report summary.
Runs \f[CR]PRAGMA integrity_check\f[R] to detect page\-level corruption,
then reports threat count, last sync time, schema version, and file
size.
Exits with code 7 if corruption is detected or the database cannot be
opened.
.TP
\f[B]logs view\f[R] [\f[B]\-\-lines\f[R] \f[I]N\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-full\f[R]]
View recent log entries (default: 100 lines).
Use \f[B]\-\-full\f[R] to show the entire log file.
.TP
\f[B]logs follow\f[R] [\f[B]\-\-lines\f[R] \f[I]N\f[R]]
Follow new log entries as they are written (tail\-f style, default 10
initial lines).
Press Ctrl+C to stop.
.SS Package Manager Commands
When invoked with a known package manager name, \f[B]pkgd\f[R]
intercepts the command:
.IP
.EX
pkgd MANAGER ARGS...
.EE
.PP
Examples:
.IP
.EX
pkgd pip install requests
pkgd npm install express
pkgd brew install tree
pkgd cargo add serde
.EE
.PP
The 19 supported invokable managers are: \f[B]apt\f[R], \f[B]brew\f[R],
\f[B]bun\f[R], \f[B]bundler\f[R], \f[B]cargo\f[R], \f[B]composer\f[R],
\f[B]conda\f[R], \f[B]dnf\f[R], \f[B]gem\f[R], \f[B]npm\f[R],
\f[B]pip\f[R], \f[B]pip3\f[R], \f[B]pipenv\f[R], \f[B]pipx\f[R],
\f[B]pnpm\f[R], \f[B]poetry\f[R], \f[B]uv\f[R], \f[B]yarn\f[R],
\f[B]yum\f[R].
