.SH WRAPPER OPTIONS
These options are accepted on every package\-manager wrapper invocation
(e.g., \f[CR]pkgd pip install ...\f[R]).
They control the protection pipeline applied to the intercepted command.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-fail\-on\-threat\f[R]
Exit with code 4 (\f[CR]EXIT_THREAT_DETECTED\f[R]) when CRITICAL or HIGH
threats are detected.
Default behavior is configurable via
\f[CR]config.fail_on_threat_enabled\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\-\-cooldown\f[R] \f[I]HOURS\f[R]
Override the cooldown window (in hours) for this invocation.
The hours value is converted to days (rounded up) and used as the
cooldown window.
Invalid values fall back to the config default.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-allow\-once\f[R] \f[I]DURATION\f[R]
Allow this single install, bypassing cooldown (default: 24h, e.g.,
\f[B]\-\-allow\-once=6h\f[R]).
Threat checks still run.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-bypass\-cooldown\f[R]
Skip the cooldown check (threat checks still run).
.TP
\f[B]\-\-bypass\-threat\f[R]
Skip the threat check (cooldown is still enforced).
.TP
\f[B]\-\-dry\-run\f[R], \f[B]\-n\f[R]
Show what would happen without making changes.
(Also a global option.)
.TP
\f[B]\-\-json\f[R]
Output result as JSON.
(Also a global option.)
.TP
\f[B]\-\-verbose\f[R], \f[B]\-v\f[R]
Increase verbosity.
(Also a global option.)
.TP
\f[B]\-\-ci\f[R], \f[B]\-\-non\-interactive\f[R]
Run in non\-interactive CI mode.
(Also a global option.)
.TP
\f[B]\-\-explain\f[R]
Show detailed explanation for blocked packages.
(Also a global option.)
.TP
\f[B]\-\-force\f[R], \f[B]\-f\f[R]
Skip confirmation prompts.
(Also a global option.)
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
\f[B]0\f[R]
Success.
.TP
\f[B]1\f[R]
General error.
.TP
\f[B]2\f[R]
Usage error (invalid arguments).
.TP
\f[B]3\f[R]
Cooldown block (package version is in cooldown period).
.TP
\f[B]4\f[R]
Threat detected (vulnerability or malicious package found) \f[B]or\f[R]
cooldown\-pending packages in \f[CR]audit\f[R] (see
\f[CR]audit.py:288\-289\f[R] for the \f[CR]audit\f[R] command\(cqs
exit\-on\-cooldown\-pending behavior).
.TP
\f[B]5\f[R]
Registry unreachable (network or registry error).
.TP
\f[B]6\f[R]
Configuration error.
.TP
\f[B]7\f[R]
Database error.
.TP
\f[B]8\f[R]
Partial failure (e.g., setup completed with warnings).
.TP
\f[B]130\f[R]
Interrupted by signal (SIGINT / Ctrl+C).
.SH FILES
.TP
\f[I]\(ti/.config/pkg\-defender/pkgd.toml\f[R]
User configuration file.
On macOS, the path is \f[I]\(ti/Library/Application
Support/pkg\-defender/pkgd.toml\f[R].
On Windows, the path is
\f[I]%APPDATA%\(rspkg\-defender\(rspkgd.toml\f[R].
The exact path is resolved via
\f[CR]platformdirs.user_config_dir(\(dqpkg\-defender\(dq)\f[R] and can
be overridden by \f[CR]PKGD_CONFIG_PATH\f[R] or \f[B]\-\-config\f[R].
.TP
\f[I]\(ti/.local/share/pkg\-defender/threats.db\f[R]
Local threat intelligence database (SQLite).
Path is resolved via
\f[CR]platformdirs.user_data_dir(\(dqpkg\-defender\(dq)\f[R] (macOS:
\f[I]\(ti/Library/Application Support/pkg\-defender/threats.db\f[R]).
.TP
\f[I]\(ti/.local/share/pkg\-defender/pkgd.log\f[R]
Application log file (rotating, 10 MB per file, 5 backups).
Path is the same data directory as \f[CR]threats.db\f[R].
.TP
\f[I]\(ti/.local/share/pkg\-defender/daemon.pid\f[R]
PID file for the background daemon.
Used by \f[CR]daemon start\f[R] / \f[CR]daemon stop\f[R] to send
SIGTERM/SIGKILL.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
\f[B]NO_COLOR\f[R]
Disable colored output (standard env var).
Takes precedence over \f[CR]config.output.color\f[R].
.TP
